WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Georgie.

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Georgie, what do you think makes a good citizen?

6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Ooh, interesting question.

7
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
I think a good citizen is someone who doesn't break the law

8
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
and is generally kind to other people. What about you?

9
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Any ideas?

10
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Yeah, I agree.

11
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:36.000
But also maybe people who volunteer, so people who run clubs for children and that kind of thing.

12
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
I think they're good citizens.

13
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Now, being a citizen, a member of society who enjoys certain rights in return for having certain responsibilities, is an old idea.

14
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
That's been in the news a lot recently.

15
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
It's something that interests Mira and Ubii,

16
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:56.000
presenter of BBC World Service Program, People Fixing the World.

17
00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
What do you think makes a good citizen?

18
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Is it someone who follows the laws of the land and pays their taxes?

19
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Well, some people might say, it should go beyond that.

20
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And a good citizen is one who tries to improve the place where they live.

21
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
A good citizen obeys the law of the land,

22
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
a term for the set of rules and laws that exist in a country.

23
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But should there be more to it than that?

24
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Around the world, young people today are less likely to vote.

25
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And many people aged 18 to 30 say they feel ignored by politicians.

26
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So in this program, we'll be hearing about my policy,

27
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
an exciting project helping young people in Portugal re-engage with their citizenship.

28
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases,

29
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
all of which you'll find on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

30
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
But before that, I have a question for you, Neil.

31
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
The project's name, my policy, comes from the ancient Greek states such as Athens and Sparta,

32
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
where the idea of citizenship was born.

33
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
So what is the meaning of the ancient Greek word,

34
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Pollis? Is it a, vote? Be people, or c, city?

35
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Hmm, that's a good question.

36
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
I'm going to guess, be people.

37
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Okay, we'll reveal the correct answer later in the program.

38
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
My policy runs council assemblies where children can propose improvements to their local school community.

39
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Anything from fixing broken water fountains to changing the curriculum.

40
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Local politicians also attend, listening to the children's ideas and responding by giving their support or explaining why not.

41
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
The project was started by founder Bernardo Gonzalez when he was in his 20s,

42
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:45.000
because he was disappointed by interactions between political parties and young people.

43
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Here's Bernardo telling more to BBC World Service program, people fixing the world.

44
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:57.000
We have seen a quick erosion in the trust of the population on the democratic institutions,

45
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
such as the National Parliament, such as the Government in office.

46
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
We need to find new ways to connect children and young citizens to the democratic institutions.

47
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Otherwise, the gap will get bigger and bigger.

48
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
This is very dangerous for democracy.

49
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Bernardo thinks Portugal has seen an erosion of trust.

50
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:25.000
A term for the gradual weakening of people's confidence in political and economic institutions and the government in office.

51
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
A government in office means the government in power at the present time.

52
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.000
My policy mirrors the political activities that children will need as adult citizens,

53
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
things like voting and holding politicians accountable.

54
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Reporter Allison Roberts visited schools around the Portuguese capital Lisbon,

55
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
and was impressed by what she saw as she explains here to myra and ubi,

56
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
presenter of BBC World Services, people fixing the world.

57
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Another benefit is my policy has designed the program so it can be included as part of the national curriculum rather than as an adult.

58
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Well, it's good to know that this is happening in other places,

59
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
but the thing that also really strikes me here is that politicians are actually listening to these kids

60
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:13.000
and taking them seriously, giving them answers because politicians as we know can be hard to pin down.

61
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
The Mypolis program is designed as part of the whole school curriculum, and not just an addon,

62
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
meaning something extra that is added later instead of being planned in from the start.

63
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
Myra was impressed that local politicians take the school children seriously.

64
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:35.000
If you take someone or something seriously, you think it's important and deserves attention.

65
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And that's good because as everyone knows, politicians can be hard to pin down.

66
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:46.000
To pin someone down means to force them to explain their plans and intentions in detail.

67
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
It sounds like the program is really developing active citizens of the future in Portugal.

68
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:58.000
In fact, it's been so successful that similar programs have been started in Italy, Hungary, and Mozambique.

69
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Okay, Neil, I think I should reveal the answer to my question.

70
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.000
I asked you what is the meaning of the ancient Greek word,

71
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Paulis, and you said, people, which was the wrong answer I'm afraid, the right answer was C, city.

72
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Oh no.

73
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Right, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with the law of the land,

74
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
a term for the set of rules and laws that exist in a country.

75
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.000
An erosion of trust happens when people gradually lose confidence in political and economic institutions.

76
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
If a government is in office, it means they are currently in power.

77
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:41.000
An add-on is an extra part that is added to something later, rather than being built in from the start.

78
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
If you take someone seriously, you consider them important and worthy of your attention.

79
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, if you find it hard to pin someone down, it's difficult to find out their specific plans and intentions.

80
00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember, you'll find a quiz and worksheet for this episode over on our website.

81
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
BBCLanningEnglish.com.

82
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
See you there soon. Bye.

83
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Goodbye.
